  }, `Welles’s attack on the Nazi system problematically relied on maintaining stereotypes of native tribes as primitive, cult-like and violent people and making direct comparisons between their actions and beliefs to that of their Nazi counterparts. This comparison is most notable when Marlow’s crew first witnesses Kurtz as he delivers a speech to praying natives. Kurtz greets the natives and they respond with a “low harmonized wail” and rise to their knees (Final Script, p. 135). As they return back to their original praying position, “the company men clumsily follow the natives’ action” (Final Script, p. 135). In this instance, Welles aligns the German crew and the praying natives, establishing their common venerance of an idolized supreme leader. The Nazis believed that they were a primitive ideal - that through their different heritages, they returned to an idealized race. However, through his engagement with fascism in this scene and throughout the script, Welles asserts that Nazis are effectively the most primitive - the epitome of a reductive, violent, and anti-modern group with behavior and thought analogous that that of stone age people. `), React.createElement(MDXTag, {
